children.text: The bulkheads have been fixed directly to the trusses, and also to the adjoining walls. This makes the non-loadbearing walls load-bearing, and not does not allow the trusses to deflect as they were designed to.
The relevant Australian Standard AS 1684 Residential Timber-Framed Construction, states in section 6.2.5.2 Internal Walls – Trussed Roofs, that
‘Non-Loadbearing walls shall be kept a minimum of 10mm below the underside of the bottom chord, or ceiling battens when used’.
Also, Australian Standard AS 4440 Installation of Nail-plated Timber Roof Trusses, states in section 2.2.2 Non-Loadbearing Walls, states that
‘Non-loadbearing walls, as designated, shall not carry any truss loading and shall not be packed to touch the underside of trusses (see Figure 2.1)’ .
Australian Standard AS 4440 Installation of Nail-plated Timber Roof Trusses, also state in Appendix B2 Camber, that

‘Trusses are built with camber to allow for the initial deflection at the take up of load and some creep (i.e. long-term deflection) as the timber settles. Thus, packing to the underside of a truss over a non-loadbearing wall may stop these deflections and in turn support the truss in an incorrect position’ .

These areas will need to be reconstructed to allow the trusses to deflect as designed, by using an alternate method to support the bulkhead, such as a lintel beam selected from AS 1684 Residential Timber-Framed Construction. There is information in clause 6.3.6.5 Lintels in Non-Loadbearing Internal Walls to assist in selection of a lintel beam for this bulkhead opening, stating that
‘Where wall openings wider than 1800mm occur in non-loadbearing walls, a lintel shall be provided and the size of the lintel shall be determined from Span Table 23’ .
The builder must establish the correct sized lintel for this bulkhead opening and install it into the wall in compliance with the requirements of AS 4440 and AS 1684.
